</table><para id="import-auto-idm1239525296">Additions with negative numbers are performed slightly differently on the three methods as shown in . First, the decimal arithmetic and the sign-and-magnitude method would change addition operations to subtraction because they keep the absolute value information. Second, the ones’ complement and two’s complement methods can do the addition directly. However, the ones’ complement method would require adding one at the end to compensate the offset by one error. Let <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">x</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">y</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> be two positive numbers. The one’s complement and two’s complement representations of negative are denoted as  y  <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>–</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">´</m:mo></m:mover><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mi>'</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">–y= acute {y} =y'</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. Therefore, we have the following:</para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm945230000">
        <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
          <m:semantics>
            <m:mrow>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                <m:mover accent="true">
                  <m:mi>y</m:mi>
                  <m:mo stretchy="false">´</m:mo>
                </m:mover>
              </m:mrow>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                <m:mrow>
                  <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="true">(</m:mo>
                  <m:mrow>
                    <m:mrow>
                      <m:msup>
                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                        <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                      </m:msup>
                      <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                      <m:mi>y</m:mi>
                      <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                      <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                    </m:mrow>
                  </m:mrow>
                  <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="true">)</m:mo>
                </m:mrow>
              </m:mrow>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                <m:mi>y</m:mi>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                <m:msup>
                  <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                  <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                </m:msup>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                <m:mn>1</m:mn>
              </m:mrow>
            </m:mrow>
            <m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">x+ acute {y} =x+ left ({2} ^ {n} -y-1 right ) =x-y+ {2} ^ {n} -1</m:annotation>
          </m:semantics>
        </m:math>
      </para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1182922640">The result of directly summing a positive and a negative number in ones’ complement representation is <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">x-y-1</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. This is the reason why we have to add one back in the ones’ complement method. Note that the term <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:msup><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:msup><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{2} ^ {n}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> results in the carry of the highest bit can be safely removed. In the two’s complement method, the offset by one error is solved upfront when the number is converted to its two’s complement representation. The mathematical relation is shown as follows:</para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm981539200">
        <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
          <m:semantics>
            <m:mrow>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                <m:msup>
                  <m:mi>y</m:mi>
                  <m:mi>'</m:mi>
                </m:msup>
              </m:mrow>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                <m:mrow>
                  <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="true">(</m:mo>
                  <m:mrow>
                    <m:mrow>
                      <m:msup>
                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                        <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                      </m:msup>
                      <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                      <m:mi>y</m:mi>
                    </m:mrow>
                  </m:mrow>
                  <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="true">)</m:mo>
                </m:mrow>
              </m:mrow>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                <m:mi>y</m:mi>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                <m:msup>
                  <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                  <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                </m:msup>
              </m:mrow>
            </m:mrow>
            <m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">x+ {y} ^ {'} =x+ left ({2} ^ {n} -y right ) =x-y+ {2} ^ {n}</m:annotation>
          </m:semantics>
        </m:math>
      </para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1048813984">The result of adding a positive number and a negative number in its two’s complement representation is equal to the result of subtracting the negative number from the positive. This is a superior characteristic of the two’s complement method compared to the ones’ complement method.  </para>
