        <image mime-type="image/png" src="draw_odg0.png"/>
      </media>
    </section>
    <section id="import-auto-idm1205509008">
      <title>Numeral Conversions</title>
      <para id="import-auto-idm994504144">Give a number represented in a numeral system, it is straightforward to convert it to a decimal number simply follow the equation <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>a</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:msub><m:mi>a</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:msub><m:mi>a</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mi>…</m:mi><m:msub><m:mi>a</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:msub><m:mi>a</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:msub><m:mi>a</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub><m:mi>.</m:mi><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mi>…</m:mi><m:mi>b</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mi>m</m:mi></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:munderover><m:mo stretchy="false">∑</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>i</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:msub><m:mi>a</m:mi><m:mi>i</m:mi></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mi>i</m:mi></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mrow><m:munderover><m:mo stretchy="false">∑</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>j</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mi>m</m:mi></m:munderover><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mi>j</m:mi></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:msup><m:mn>10</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mi>j</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{a} rsub {n-1} {a} rsub {n-2} {a} rsub {n-3} … {a} rsub {2} {a} rsub {1} {a} rsub {0} . {b} rsub {0} {b} rsub {1} {…b} rsub {m-1} {b} rsub {m} = sum from {i=0} to {n-1} {{a} rsub {i}} × {r} ^ {i} + sum from {j=0} to {m} {{b} rsub {j}} × {10} ^ {-j}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, where <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:msub><m:mi>a</m:mi><m:mi>i</m:mi></m:msub><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{a} rsub {i}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> ’s are the integral digits, <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mi>j</m:mi></m:msub><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{b} rsub {j}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> ’s are the fraction digits, and <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">r</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is the radix. It is harder to do the reverse conversions. Consider a conversion from a decimal integer to a base- <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">r</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> numeral system, <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>d</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mi>…</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:msup><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">d= {b} rsub {n-1} × {2} ^ {n-1} +…+ {b} rsub {1} × {2} ^ {1} + {b} rsub {0} × {2} ^ {0}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, where <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>d</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">d</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is a decimal integer and <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mi>i</m:mi></m:msub><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{b} rsub {i}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> ’s are binary digits. Our goal is to find all the binary digits <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mi>i</m:mi></m:msub><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{b} rsub {i}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> ’s. A closer look at the equation will find that the last term in the right hand side is actually <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{b} rsub {0}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, which is either 0 or 1. If we try to divide both sides by 2, the following equation is derived:</para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1058463840">
        <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
          <m:semantics>
            <m:mrow>
              <m:mfrac>
                <m:mi>d</m:mi>
                <m:mn>2</m:mn>
              </m:mfrac>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mrow>
                  <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
                  <m:mrow>
                    <m:mrow>
                      <m:msub>
                        <m:mi>b</m:mi>
                        <m:mrow>
                          <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                          <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                      </m:msub>
                      <m:mi>×</m:mi>
                      <m:mrow>
                        <m:msup>
                          <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                          <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                            <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                          </m:mrow>
                        </m:msup>
                        <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>…</m:mi>
                        <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                        <m:msub>
                          <m:mi>b</m:mi>
                          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                        </m:msub>
                      </m:mrow>
                      <m:mi>×</m:mi>
                      <m:mrow>
                        <m:msup>
                          <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                        </m:msup>
                        <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                        <m:msub>
                          <m:mi>b</m:mi>
                          <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                        </m:msub>
                      </m:mrow>
                      <m:mi>×</m:mi>
                      <m:msup>
                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                        <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                      </m:msup>
                    </m:mrow>
                  </m:mrow>
                  <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
                </m:mrow>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">/</m:mo>
                <m:mn>2</m:mn>
              </m:mrow>
            </m:mrow>
            <m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{d} over {2} =( {b} rsub {n-1} × {2} ^ {n-1} +…+ {b} rsub {1} × {2} ^ {1} + {b} rsub {0} × {2} ^ {0} )/2</m:annotation>
          </m:semantics>
        </m:math>
      </para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm355018992">Let <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>q</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">q</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> be the quotient and <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:msub><m:mi>d</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{d} rsub {0}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> be the remainder of <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>d</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">/</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">d/2</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. In the right hand side, all terms except the last one are divisible by 2. We have the following:</para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1197853280">
        <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
          <m:semantics>
            <m:mrow>
              <m:mn>2</m:mn>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mrow>
                  <m:mi>q</m:mi>
                  <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                  <m:msub>
                    <m:mi>d</m:mi>
                    <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                  </m:msub>
                </m:mrow>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo>
                <m:mn>2</m:mn>
              </m:mrow>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mrow>
                  <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
                  <m:mrow>
                    <m:mrow>
                      <m:msub>
                        <m:mi>b</m:mi>
                        <m:mrow>
                          <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                          <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                      </m:msub>
                      <m:mi>×</m:mi>
                      <m:mrow>
                        <m:msup>
                          <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                          <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                            <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                          </m:mrow>
                        </m:msup>
                        <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>…</m:mi>
                        <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                        <m:msub>
                          <m:mi>b</m:mi>
                          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                        </m:msub>
                      </m:mrow>
                      <m:mi>×</m:mi>
                      <m:msup>
                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                        <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                      </m:msup>
                    </m:mrow>
                  </m:mrow>
                  <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
                </m:mrow>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                <m:msub>
                  <m:mi>b</m:mi>
                  <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                </m:msub>
              </m:mrow>
            </m:mrow>
            <m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">2q+ {d} rsub {0} =2( {b} rsub {n-1} × {2} ^ {n-2} +…+ {b} rsub {1} × {2} ^ {0} )+ {b} rsub {0}</m:annotation>
          </m:semantics>
        </m:math>
      </para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1014255472">Based on this relation, <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>d</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{b} rsub {0} = {d} rsub {0}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, i.e., the remainder of <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>d</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">/</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">d/2</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. Since <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>d</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{b} rsub {0} = {d} rsub {0}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, we can take it out from both sides of the above equation. The following relation is obtained.</para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1005629120">
        <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
          <m:semantics>
            <m:mrow>
              <m:mn>2</m:mn>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mrow>
                  <m:mi>q</m:mi>
                  <m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo>
                  <m:msub>
                    <m:mi>d</m:mi>
                    <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                  </m:msub>
                  <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                  <m:msub>
                    <m:mi>d</m:mi>
                    <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                  </m:msub>
                </m:mrow>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo>
                <m:mn>2</m:mn>
              </m:mrow>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mrow>
                  <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="true">(</m:mo>
                  <m:mrow>
                    <m:mrow>
                      <m:msub>
                        <m:mi>b</m:mi>
                        <m:mrow>
                          <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                          <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                      </m:msub>
                      <m:mi>×</m:mi>
                      <m:mrow>
                        <m:msup>
                          <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                          <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                            <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                          </m:mrow>
                        </m:msup>
