      <para id="import-auto-idm338594736">The equation shows the relation between <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>q</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">q</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and its binary representation, which is similar to the original equation. Again, all we need to do is find the remainder of <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>q</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">/</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">q/2</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, and let <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{b} rsub {1}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> be the remainder. The rest of the <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mi>i</m:mi></m:msub><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{b} rsub {i}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> ’s will be obtained in this manner repeatedly. In general, any bases can be computed in this way. For example, converting 57 to binary involves the steps shown in . Here we keep a long division upside down and only write down quotients and remainders. The remainders are kept in the right hand side. Keep doing this process until the quotient is less than the base, or 2 in this example. The result reads from the bottom up. In this case, it is 111001, which is the binary representation of 57.</para>
