    <section id="import-auto-idm1218393888">
      <title>Decimal to Hexadecimal Integers</title>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1862013280">The conversion from decimal to hexadecimal involves divisions by 16, which is the base of hexadecimal numerals. Like binary conversions, all we need is find the remainders during the divisions. For example, convert 1234 to hexadecimal as shown in . The quotient 77 is obtained by performing the division 1234/16 on a side (not shown on the table). The readers should work this on a piece of scratch paper to avoid errors. As can be seen that hexadecimal conversion from decimal involves much less divisions, the example only takes 2 divisions. The result is read from bottom up again. Thus, 1234 in hexadecimal is 4D2. The result can be verified by <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mn>4</m:mn><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mn>16</m:mn><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mn>13</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mn>16</m:mn><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>1234</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">4× {16} ^ {2} +13× {16} ^ {1} +2=1234</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
