    <section id="import-auto-idm1033068512">
      <title>Hexadecimal to Binary</title>
      <para id="import-auto-idm938464624">From hexadecimal to binary, all we need is convert each individual hexadecimal digit to binary. This is done. Why? Here is the explanation. We first look at the definition of a hexadecimal number.</para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1237605360"><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mi>…</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mn>16</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mi>…</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mn>16</m:mn><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{h} rsub {n-1} {h} rsub {n-2…} {h} rsub {1} {h} rsub {0} = {h} rsub {n-1} × {16} ^ {n-1} +…+ {h} rsub {1} × {16} ^ {1} + {h} rsub {0}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> where <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mi>i</m:mi></m:msub><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{h} rsub {i}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> ’s are hexadecimal digits.</para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1214282064">If we convert each hexadecimal digit to binary, the following equation is derived:</para>
