      <para id="import-auto-idm1165709456">Now, let’s turn to the conversion from decimal numbers to <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">r</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>-nary numbers. Remember that converting the integral part of a decimal number involves divisions. The fraction part conversion is done using multiplications. Consider an <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">r</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>-nary numeral system and a fraction in decimal <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">f</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">&lt;</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">f&lt;1</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, we have the following</para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm978246656"><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mi>…</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:msup><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo fence="true" stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mo fence="true" stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">f= {b} rsub {1} × {r} ^ {-1} + {b} rsub {2} × {r} ^ {-2} +…+ {b} rsub {n-1} × {r} ^ {-(n-1)}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm977115120">Our goal is to find all the <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mi>j</m:mi></m:msub><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{b} rsub {j}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> ’s. If both sides of the above equation are multiplied by <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">r</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, this yields</para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1166284688"><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mi>…</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:msup><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo fence="true" stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mo fence="true" stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">f×r= {b} rsub {1} + {b} rsub {2} × {r} ^ {-1} +…+ {b} rsub {n-1} × {r} ^ {-(n-2)}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1182806480">To satisfy the equality, we can pick <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{b} rsub {1}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> to be the integral part of <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mi>r</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">f×r</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, and the fraction part of <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mi>r</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">f×r</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> will be the rest of terms in the right hand side, i.e., <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mi>…</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:msup><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo fence="true" stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mo fence="true" stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{b} rsub {2} × {r} ^ {-1} +…+ {b} rsub {n-1} × {r} ^ {-(n-2)}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> . Follow this procedure, we can get <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mi>,</m:mi><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:msub><m:mi>,</m:mi><m:mi>…</m:mi><m:mi>,</m:mi><m:msub><m:mi>b</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{b} rsub {2} ,  {b} rsub {3} , …, {b} rsub {n-1}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. For example, converting the decimal <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mn>0.03046875</m:mn><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">0.03046875</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> to octal is illustrated in . In the first row, the multiplication result is <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mn>2.4375</m:mn><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">2.4375</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, which is composed of the integer <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">2</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and the fraction <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mn>0.4375</m:mn><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">0.4375</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. The integer 2 will be the first positional octal fraction digit, and the fraction will be used for finding the second positional octal fraction digit. Therefore, the result confirms that <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mn>0.03046875</m:mn><m:mn>10</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mn>0.234</m:mn><m:mn>8</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{0.03046875} rsub {10} = {0.234} rsub {8}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> as illustrated in the previous example. </para>
